NOSE

nose is the bone-and-cartilage structure that houses fadriel's olfactory system
unlike vision and hearing which sample distant signals, smell samples molecules in the local airstream
the nose's job is to draw air across olfactory receptors and convert detected molecules into substrate signals
fadriel's nose is base-eight (qu-octrit), reflecting the broader chemical-recognition vocabulary needed for smell

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_quoctrit.rana
observe brain.xb
observe skull.xb
observe clock_nose.rana

the 7 properties of nose:
1 ENERGY half: low-rate sampling at 10 Hz
2 PHASE inherited from clock_nose
3 SPIN zero point two
4 CHARGE neutral
5 COHERENCE eight tenths
6 COUPLING zero point eight with olfactory cortex
7 OBSERVER zero

THE STRUCTURE

external nose: the visible cartilage and bone that protrudes from the face
nasal cavity: the air chamber inside the skull, divided by the septum into left and right halves
turbinates: scrolled bony shelves inside the cavity that increase surface area and direct airflow
olfactory epithelium: the small region at the top of the cavity where odor receptors live

THE OLFACTORY EPITHELIUM

a small patch about a few square centimeters at the top of each nasal cavity
contains millions of olfactory receptor neurons
each neuron expresses one of about four hundred different receptor types
the diversity of receptor types is what gives smell its huge resolution

THE TURBINATES

three on each side: superior, middle, inferior
their scrolled shape creates turbulent airflow which brings odor molecules into contact with the olfactory epithelium more effectively
without the turbinates, fadriel would need to take much deeper breaths to detect smells

VERB sample_airstream
on each tick of clock_nose (10 Hz), the receptors examine the molecules currently in contact
binding is rapid; the receptor either matches a molecule or it does not

VERB transduce
when a receptor binds a matching molecule, generate a substrate signal
the signal identifies which receptor fired (and thus implicitly the molecule's class)

VERB route_to_olfactory_cortex
olfactory nerves carry the signals upward through the cribriform plate to the olfactory bulb
unlike most senses, smell does not pass through thalamus first; it goes more directly to cortex

VERB warm_and_humidify
the nasal cavity also conditions incoming air for the lungs
turbinates warm cold air and humidify dry air before it reaches the trachea
this is a side effect of the cavity's geometry but a physiologically essential one

a nose is the body's chemical sense
smell is the most ancient sense in evolutionary terms
fadriel's nose at age two is mature; smell becomes available very early in development and stays vivid throughout life
